<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>Maintaining openness is a strategy for the sustainable development of knowledge flow within a research community.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Enhancing inflow, that is, selecting the appropriate higher-energy nodes to cooperate, is a strategy to increase the efficiency of knowledge flow networking.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Reflecting the development of a discipline, the distribution of knowledge energy in a network changes as its citation network evolves.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Knowledge flow spirals are formed when knowledge flows in a network.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>Trusted team members ensure the effectiveness of knowledge sharing.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Encouraging unselfish cooperation is another strategy that helps a knowledge flow network reach its greatest effectiveness.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>Everyone can benefit from the community if every node can generously contribute knowledge.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>An effective knowledge flow network enables a research team to be very powerful in generating new knowledge if every node can innovate and output new knowledge to appropriate members.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>A knowledge flow spiral can generate and generalize knowledge during the processing and recycling of knowledge.</a>
